stylometry: Fixed cost models usually determine whether incurring certain fixed costs to produce a given product are beneficial to a company.  In set covering models, every value from set A must correspond to a value in set B.  An example of a fixed cost model:  Line A has fixed costs of $10,000, variable costs are $100 per unit, and can produce 100 units a day.  Line B has fixed costs of $5,000, variable costs are $100 per unit, and can produce 65 units a day.  A fixed cost model can be used to determine which is more beneficial.
